Quote:<br>
Please correct me if I’m wrong Brutus, but are you saying in a roundabout way that with true love, understanding and spiritual growth comes... Discernment and wisdom?<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
It wasn’t my goal to say that in a roundabout way, but I do agree with you Rheaton.  I think that is part of the process.  <br>
<br>
Quote:<br>
There is a since of urgency to reach as many people as possible.<br>
<br>
Yea, I think so.  Unfortunately however, just because you are a professor doesn’t mean you are good teacher.  Have you ever had a professor in college who was an absolute genius in a certain academic area, but was the worst teacher?  I imagine some people might attain a high level of status in a religious institution based on their academic skills, but probably insult people or turn them off because communicating to people on such touchy topics is an art and not a dry instructional manual; unless of course you have developed a special relationship with that person.  I’m not trying to frustrate anyone from expressing his or her thoughts and feelings; rather I’m suggesting humility when doing so.  It is not actually the fault of Christian religions that they seem so arrogant, it’s a numbers thing.<br>
<br>
 You would NEVER see a Buddhist or Hindu institution ‘spreading’ their faith in such a fashion.  Why not you say, Because they would be lynched!!  They remain humble in the interest of preservation.  Circumstantially, they are good diplomats for their Religious institution.  Christian institutions however, do not have a preservation problem and are dominant, so of course, since they are on the ‘number 1 team’, they tend to do the hip-hip hooray dance.  It’s a human nature thing.  This is why I don’t prefer human made institutions, especially religious ones.  I don’t think its ‘bad’ to go to church, but it reminds me of how hypocritical we all can be.  Sometimes I would rather just focus on love rather than truth.  <br>
<br>
I think people take the bible way out of context at times.  If they don’t ‘spread’ the word, that Druid tree worshipper might go to hell.  I have a hard time believing God would use guilt as a motivator for increasing his ‘manmade’ institution.  What a turn off!  “If you don’t turn him, he will go to hell and it will be your fault.  You will be a loser and that is not acceptable for my team.  How could you just let someone go to hell? You must be evil!  You have disappointed God, Jesus and the Holy Ghost and now you will drown in your own purgatory!”  <br>
<br>
What a bunch of freeks!!    (I’m not at all directing that towards you Lukaria)  It’s a stereotype, but a very real one.  <br>
<br>
