Rheaton, it is interesting to note "...a hard one to swallow if your not prepared to hear it spiritually."<br>
<br>
I can appreciate the spirituality of others even if I believe they are mistaken doctrinally. What does that mean? I am glad you asked. :)<br>
<br>
It means that "spirituality" is had by anyone that is mindfull of sacred matters. I know some Christians who would deny that persons like Gandhi were not <i><b>truly</i></b>spiritual because they were not Christians. Imagine that, if you can, Mahatma Gandhi was not spiritual because he practiced the Hindu religion! /boggle<br>
<br>
What is even more mind boggling to me is those Christians who sincerely believe people like Mahatma Gandhi will burn in hell along side with Adolph Hitler!<br>
<br>
There is a difference between believing one has the truth and being secure in one's belief. Those who are secure in their beliefs really don't try to peddle them on the street corner.<br>
<br>
Some Christians may like to think that others are not "prepared to hear... spiritually" when their message is rejected. But isn't that just attempting to place blame on the individuals who don't want to hear the message rather than on the message itself? God forbid that anyone would actually find the Christian message lacking! :) Those damn degenerate atheists, Muslims, Jews, and Hindus (to name a few) are all sad spiritual wrecks! LOL<br>
<br>
There may be an eternity of life and happiness. And this being so, if there were an infinite number of chances at that life, but only one path, you would still be right in wagering on a single path. However, it would be stupid to assume one's wager is better than another's. If there is here an infinity of paths to an infinitely happy life, a chance of gain against a finite number of chances of loss, and what <i>you stake is finite</i>. Understanding that your stake is finite against an infinity of paths should drive one to 1) not wager at all realizing that happiness in this life is the most important; 2) or wager knowing that anyone's bet, being finite, is just as good as any other. <br>
<br>
Rheaton, you have your wager at the table just as I do. I believe it is important to respect all bets on the table knowing that the other gamblers at the table are doing their best just as you are. When it come to an after life we are all really just wagering. However, we don't have to bet on happiness now. We can just have it. <p><center><font face="arial" color="CCFFFF">Lurikeen Mali'Kyre</FONT></center><center><table style='Filter: Shadow(Color=#150517, Direction=225)'><tr><td><span class='Necromancer'><font size=2 color="red" face="arial"><i>NECROMANCER</span></td></tr></table></font></i></center><center><font face=arial></center><center><I>"My eyes will pierce your soul, then I will take your life!"</I></center></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ulurikeen.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Lurikeen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 808<br> <font color=#E9D756>(6/10/02 8:14:16 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrfrm18.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=302.topic&index=109>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Waaaaaaazup!</span><hr size=1> I meant to write the following: "I know some Christians who would deny that persons like Gandhi were <i><b>truly</b></i> spiritual because they were not Christians."<br>
