 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ulurikeen.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Lurikeen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 809<br> <font color=#E9D756>(6/11/02 9:37:50 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrfrm18.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=302.topic&index=115>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Waaaaaaazup!</span><hr size=1> <i>"I will tell you this much.. and I dare to cause I know "carnal logic" will be applied.... But if you have never had the spirit of God in you, you really have no idea about Christianity."</i><br>
<br>
Yes, I have been presented this answer before, Rheaton. There are a couple self-evident problems with it.<br>
<br>
1) <b>The rejection of logical reasoning.</b> Once a person claims that reasoning can't be applied in order to gain understanding, then there is nothing more to be talked about. Notice that there is a difference between the claim that logic can't be employed to discuss an experience from some experiences are ineffable. Ineffable experiences can be talked about, but only via analogy which is subject to logical reasoning.<br>
<br>
2) <b>The idea that one who has never had the spirit of god can't understand Christianity<b> is self refuting. First, how does one know they have the "spirit of God" in them? By your own admission we can't logically discuss (or know) that one has the true spirit of god in them. Furthermore, even Christians are divided as to what counts as having the spirit of God. Pentecostals are going to tell Baptists that they must speak in tongues and some Baptists will say that speaking in tongues is of the devil! Point being, the experience of having the "spirit of god" is <i>private</i>. Meaning that it is not a public event and not knowable. Saying, "I know blah, blah is true" is not enough if you can't talk about it logically. For instance, what does "true" mean in such circumstances? "True" has no meaning with private experiences, since logic can't be applied.<br>
<br>
The upshot is that you can neither know you have the true "spirit of god" or meaningfully say things such as "It is true that I have the spirit of god in me". So, even those who claim to have the spirit of god really don't <i>know</i> Christianity... if we can't apply logic or talk rationally about the experience.<br>
<br>
In addition... since having the "spirit of god" is a private experience how can you meaningfully say others don't have his spirit? If you can say that others do have his spirit then having the spirit of god is a public experience which is subject to logical discourse (talking about it). In which case we can apply logic.<br>
<br>
I will end here for the moment.<br>
