<br>
What I was pointing out is that if having the spirit of god is a non-analyzable private experience, as you seem to indicate that it is, then you can't know if someone has the spirit of god in them or not. Indeed, the larger issue is one couldn't meaningfully say things such as "That person truly has the spirit of god in them."<br>
<br>
Given that, it makes no sense to judge others as having or not having the "spirit of god". In which case, "understanding Christianity" is something nobody can really do. <p><center><font face="arial" color="CCFFFF">Lurikeen Mali'Kyre</FONT></center><center><table style='Filter: Shadow(Color=#150517, Direction=225)'><tr><td><span class='Necromancer'><font size=2 color="red" face="arial"><i>NECROMANCER</span></td></tr></table></font></i></center><center><font face=arial></center><center><I>"My eyes will pierce your soul, then I will take your life!"</I></center></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/urheaton.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Rheaton</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 234<br> <font color=#E9D756>(6/11/02 12:26:52 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrfrm18.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=302.topic&index=120>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Waaaaaaazup!</span><hr size=1> That is where spiritual perception and discernment comes in. I can say &quot;That guy truly has the spirit of God in him..&quot; and actually feel and believe it. I cannot prove it to the flesh.... but I can feel it with a sense of certainty.<br>
<br>
This spiritual perception and discernment is where most Christian's operate.<br>
<br>
So yes.. two people with the same spirit of God within them can indeed understand Christianity mutually.<br>
